  Here's the Punchline, There's More to It
  
.content.
  Not all Asian or Asian American males are typecasted
  as the kung-fu master; that role requires a certain
  character and physique. The other Asian men 
  who have graced US media did so through another
  role: the clown, the jester, the butt of the joke.
  Remember <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_hung">
  William Hung</a>? Despite his terrible performance
  on <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Idol">
  American Idol</a>, his appearance on the show 
  garnered him international stardom and even a record
  deal.<div class="citation"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_hung">19</a></div>
  He had no talent (he said so himself), 
  fit the look of a stereotypical nerdy
  Asian, and spoke with a noticeable accent.
  Many have attributed his fame to mockery and 
  white hegemonic propagation of entrenched
  Asian sterotypes. In other words, he stood 
  in front of US media as a joke.<div class="citation"><a href="http://www.sfgate.com/politics/article/William-Hung-Racism-Or-Magic-2798362.php">20</a></div>
  <iframe width="420" height="315" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/0d5eP0wWLQY" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen>
  </iframe>
  <br /><br />
  More recently, US pop culture has taken a liking
  to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ken_Jeong">
  Dr. Ken Jeong</a>. Better known as Leslie Chow
  in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hangover_(franchise)">
  The Hangover film series</a> or  
  <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Community_characters#Ben_Chang">
  Ben Chang</a> in NBC commedy series <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Community_(TV_series)">
  Community</a>, Jeong, an MD born in the US to South
  Korean parents, has been playing the role
  of the Asian clown, clad with a heavy 
  <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fresh_off_the_boat">
  fresh off the boat</a> accent and 
  peculiar persona. Need explicit proof? Watch this
  clip from the first Hangover film. 
  <iframe width="560" height="315" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/jGMFwT3iSMk" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>
  <br /><br />
  While PSY is neither Hung or Jeong, it is clear
  that he has found his way into US pop culture
  through the jokester stereotype; he built his 
  career on being the funny-guy.<div class="citation"><a href="http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-12-23/news-and-interviews/35982239_1_psy-south-korean-rapper-dance">21</a></div>

