  You're Either a Fighter or a Comedian and Never a Man

.content.
  Why have these two stereotypes prevailed in US pop
  culture? Given that mainstream media is guarded by 
  the powers that be (the white heterosexual American
  male hegemonic power structure), it is clear that 
  these Asian male constructs are the results
  of the filtering of inbounding Asian characters
  and culture. These constructs are what the white
  mainstream culture rulers find acceptable
  and non-threatening. What does this mean for Korean
  and Asian masculinity in the US? Either 
  it is packaged in the familiar form of the 
  asexual martial arts master or the emasculated Asian 
  clown. I just want to add another notable example of the 
  first (in addition to those above): <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jet_Li">
  Jet Li</a> as the lead in 
  <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Romeo_Must_Die">
  Romeo Must Die</a> (his first leading role in a Hollywood
  film). The directors pre-screened the a 
  version of the film which contained a scenen
  where Li kisses the female protagonist, but
  because audiences abjectly opposed the scene
  (they boo'ed), the final version of the film
  replaced the scene with one in which Li 
  remains the platonic friend.<div class="citation"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Romeo_Must_Die">22</a></div>
  All he did in the film was fight, he was prevented from 
  having a love interest (even though the movie was 
  titled as such). But it didn't matter, he was asexual, and therefore posed no threat to
  the white hegemony, so he was acceptable.
  The same situation takes place with Rain in <i>Ninja Assassin</i>.
  <br /><br />
  With the Asian clown stereotype, masculinity 
  isn't even a part of the character.
  <br /><br />
  This protection by the hegemony may be why traditional
  Korean pop male artists have been unable to 
  successfully penetrate US pop culture. The 
  industry standard stars are dressed in high
  fashion and are always willing to show off their
  hard bodies (pretty much required by the industry).
  These stars are highly sexualized, and they 
  pose a threat to white masculinity. They are not
  deemed acceptable by the hegemony, and thus 
  they have not found their way into US pop culture
  despite having tried and with much more effort
  than PSY did.<div class="citation"><a href="http://www.racialicious.com/2012/09/20/psy-and-the-acceptable-asian-man/">4</a></div>
  In fact, PSY, who disarmed the
  gates of US pop culture with his clown persona,
  did not approach the US audiences. It was the
  other way around.
  

